>

<p class="body">Coffee is the first and last impression of a hotel stay for most guests. Morning coffee before checkout. The lobby café on the way to a meeting. In-room coffee at 6am before an early flight. These moments don't require elaborate coffee programs — but they do require coffee that's genuinely good rather than merely functional.</p>

<p class="body">The gap between functional hotel coffee and good hotel coffee has narrowed dramatically as specialty roasters have built out hospitality-specific wholesale programs. This guide covers how to close that gap at your property.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Why Coffee Matters More Than <em>Hotels Think</em></h2>

<p class="body">Hotel F&B teams often underestimate coffee's role in guest experience, because coffee rarely shows up as a line item on satisfaction surveys. What does show up: overall breakfast experience, lobby ambiance, and morning experience scores — all of which are meaningfully influenced by coffee quality.</p>

<p class="body">More directly: coffee is one of the most mentioned F&B items in hotel guest reviews on TripAdvisor and Google. Properties with excellent coffee programs see it reflected in reviews ("the coffee here is genuinely excellent, highly recommend the café"). Properties with bad coffee see it too ("everything was fine but the coffee was terrible"). For a segment where 4.5-star reviews drive booking decisions, the coffee program is not a peripheral detail.</p>

