<h2 class="section-head">The Multi-Touchpoint <em>Coffee Program</em></h2>

<p class="body">A hotel coffee program has to work across multiple contexts simultaneously. Each touchpoint has different requirements, and a good roaster partnership accounts for all of them.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">The lobby café</h3>
<p class="body">The lobby café is your highest-visibility coffee touchpoint and your biggest opportunity for both revenue and impression. Guests who want specialty coffee — travelers from coffee-literate markets, business travelers who drink well at home — will evaluate this space carefully. A well-stocked café with quality espresso, a rotating <a href="/learn/single-origin-coffee-guide" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">single-origin</a> on the pour-over bar, and staff who know what they're serving makes a statement about the property. A kiosk with a capsule machine does not.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">All-day dining</h3>
<p class="body">All-day dining coffee needs to be consistent, reliable, and executable by a team that isn't primarily focused on coffee. A well-calibrated batch brew program paired with a quality specialty blend is almost always the right call here. The goal is excellence in the cup without requiring barista-level attention during breakfast service.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">The signature restaurant</h3>
<p class="body">A hotel restaurant with culinary ambitions deserves a coffee program that matches. This might mean a single-origin offering sourced to complement the regional cuisine, an after-dinner espresso program using a roaster with a connection to the restaurant's culinary identity, or a rotating lot program that changes seasonally alongside the menu.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">In-room coffee</h3>
<p class="body">In-room coffee is where the widest gap between hotel aspiration and guest experience exists. The superautomatic machine in the room runs a pod or capsule that most guests know isn't the same as what's in the café. The most forward-thinking hotels are addressing this with curated ground coffee from the property's primary roaster — the same product, in a different format, connecting the in-room experience to the broader program.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Choosing a Roaster for <em>Hospitality</em></h2>

<p class="body">Not every specialty roaster has built a hospitality-ready wholesale program. Our <a href="/learn/best-specialty-coffee-roasters" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">guide to the best specialty roasters in the US</a> covers the five strongest options for wholesale accounts in depth. A roaster who works primarily with independent cafés may not have the packaging formats, delivery logistics, or multi-format program design that a hotel property requires. Evaluate specifically:</p>

<ul class="body-list">
  <li><strong>Multi-format offering:</strong> Can they supply whole bean for the café, pre-ground for the restaurant, and a curated in-room format from the same sourcing program?</li>
  <li><strong>Volume capacity:</strong> A hotel using 100+ lbs per week needs a roaster with the production capacity to fulfill consistently. Smaller craft roasters can be excellent partners for boutique properties; high-volume properties need a roaster with scale.</li>
  <li><strong>Hospitality experience:</strong> Ask for references from other hotel accounts. A roaster who understands the hospitality context — service recovery, multi-department coordination, seasonal volume fluctuations — is a more valuable partner than one who's adapting a café program on the fly.</li>
  <li><strong>Staff training:</strong> Hotel coffee staff turn over. A roaster who offers ongoing training rather than one-time onboarding is an asset in a high-turnover environment.</li>
  <li><strong>Local story:</strong> A locally roasted coffee program is a differentiator for guests who care about local sourcing and regional identity. If your property leans into local character, a roaster from the same market amplifies that story.</li>
</ul>

<h2 class="section-head">Making the <em>Business Case</em></h2>

<p class="body">The incremental cost of a specialty coffee program over a commercial one is real and needs to be justified to ownership and F&B leadership. The case is built on three factors.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Revenue:</strong> A quality café program generates meaningfully more revenue per square foot than a commodity kiosk. Guests who trust the café will spend more there and more frequently. Higher average ticket on coffee and pastry, higher repeat usage by in-house guests, and external traffic from neighborhood guests are all revenue benefits of a quality program.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>ADR positioning:</strong> Properties that command premium rates need premium experiences across all touchpoints. Coffee is a visible, daily touchpoint that either supports or undermines the overall premium positioning. A $400/night property serving commodity coffee creates cognitive dissonance. A $400/night property serving excellent specialty coffee reinforces why the rate is justified.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Review differentiation:</strong> In a market where online reviews drive booking decisions, a consistently mentioned positive in the coffee category is a durable competitive advantage. Build the program, execute it consistently, and let guests tell the story for you.</p>

